Introduction¶

Every human oprates in a system of global economy which include: production, consumption, economic management, work in general, exchange of financial values and trade of goods and services within and outside their countries. The aim of this project is to review our collective performances over the years seeing that we have come a long way

Dataset Description¶

The data we would be using to explore how the world economy has performed over the years is a public dataset and it is available for dowload on Gap Minder. However, there was no comprehensive data detailing the countries and their continents on Gap Minder which was why the continents' dataset was sourced from Our World in Data

Data Dictionary¶

  • country: The countries of the world

  • continent: The continents of the world

  • year : The year for each record

  • agro: Expressed as a percentage of GDP. It respresents the value of agricultural products delivered to the world

  • import:Expressed as a percentage of GDP and it respresents the value of goods and other market services recieved from the rest of the world

  • Export: Expressed as a percentage of GDP and it respresents the value of goods and other market services delivered to the rest of the world

  • investment:Expressed as a percentage of GDP and it respresents the value financial services delivered to the rest of the world

  • industry: Expressed as a percentage of GDP and it respresents the value of industrial products delivered to the world

  • Services: Expressed as a percentage of GDP and it respresents the value Services delivered to the world

  • gdp: Gross Domestic Product converted to international Dollar using power parity rate

N:B The above listed columns are contained in cleaned dataset

Questions for Analysis¶

  1. How has the world economy performed over the years?
  2. What is the general trend displayed by all continents?
  3. How do they differ in economic activites?

The need to transpose¶

Majority of all the datset are in wide format as shown above. Hence the need to transpose them. In pandas, the melt() function does the trick.

In [4]:
#create a function that performs the melts the operation 
def transpose(df,var):
    df=pd.melt(df, id_vars='country', var_name='year', value_name=var)
    return(df)

#*********************************************************************#
#melt the dataset accordingly
agric_df=transpose(agric_df,"agro")
export_df=transpose(export_df,"export")
import_df=transpose(import_df,"import")
industry_df=transpose(industry_df,"industry")
investment_df=transpose(investment_df,'investment')
services_df=transpose(services_df,"services")
gdp_df=transpose(gdp_df,"gdp")

Merge all dataset together¶

All the data read into pandas will be merged into a single dataframe using "inner join."

similarities in the dataset

  • geo_df has column "Entity" which is equivalent to 'country' column in agric_df.
  • The others have "country" and "year" in common as columns

The geo_df and agric_df will be merged first and separately. The resulting dataframe will then be merged with others

#create a function that merges all other dataset at once
def merge(df,others):
    for i,v in enumerate(others):
        df=pd.merge(df,others[i],on=['country','year'])
    return df

merged_df=merge(df,data_set)

Data Wrangling¶

At a glance the data looks too dirty. There are lots of empty entries which are not useful in the analysis. Their presence will only cause more harm than good. Hence, the need to sort out the NaN and subsequently get the data to be clean

At this point, it is necessary to stress that the GDP, "gdp" column is the dependent variable. Any empty cell there will not be tolerated. As such, they will be dropped.

Likewise, all the rows in which all the following variables,agro, import, export, investment, services are empty will be dropped.

# B-Billion,M-Million,TR-Trillion
dic = {
    'B': '1000000000',
    'TR': '1000000000000',
    'M': '1000000'
}

merged_df['gdp_format'] = merged_df['unit_char'].replace(dic).astype(float)
merged_df['gdp_format']=merged_df['gdp_fig'].astype(float)*merged_df['gdp_format']
merged_df.drop(columns=["gdp","gdp_fig","unit_char","empty_cells"],inplace=True)

data cleaning bothering on outliers, data types and null values(NaN)¶

  1. All numeric data in our data are expressed in percentage except gdp and year. As such, any value >=100 is not realistic. Besides, no country has been reported to have achieved such milestone in many years.

  2. check all data types

  3. Fill NaN with the mean of their their respective countries.

  4. And lastly, any NaN after step 3 will be dropped eventually

In [16]:
#create a function that fills NaN with mean per country of any numeric column
def fil(df,col):
    dict=df.groupby(["country"])[str(col)].mean().dropna().to_dict()
    df.loc[df[str(col)].isnull(), str(col)] = new_df['country'].map(dict)
    return df

#stepwisely fill NaN across the columns
fil_agro_na=fil(new_df,'agro') 
fil_industry=fil(fil_agro_na,'industry')
fil_investment=fil(fil_industry,'investment')
fil_services=fil(fil_investment,"services")

#drop all other null values
cleaned_data=fil_services.dropna().drop(labels='index',axis=1)

Findings from the chart¶

Bewteen 1960-2013, the world's average GDP was 41.62 Trillion and Asia presented as the largest continent among others accounting for 35.2% of world's mean GDP. This align with a more recent study carried out by statistics Times. Oceania on the other hand comprised 1.3% followed by Africa with 6.7%, while Europe and North America's GDP combined is just over half of GDP. It is important to stress that this is the weighted avrerage of the gross and did not speak for a fact of the underlying trends. It would be neccesary to get into more details to know what played out throughout the period.

Findings¶

Overall, all the continents showed an upward trend in economic growth throughout the period. However, Asia, Europe and North America experienced a surge in GDP growth since 1970 and have made dramatic progress over the years. A more recent study by statistics Times reveals similar trends.

Between 1970 and 1990, Asia led North America and Europe marginally. However, in 1990 and beyond, economic growth appereared to be overwhelmingly in support of the Asian continent. It will be crucial to find out what played out that Asia displayed sucha remarkable growth in that period. The graph clearly suggests something different about economic activities in Asia compared to the rest of the world.

It will be necessary to grill down to the key economic metrics of the continents. Perhaps, it will become clear what the Asian continent had found out and had improved on

How do the continents differ in terms of export, industry and investments?¶

In this part of the project, certain key economic contributors to the GDP will be invesigated to reveal the economic strength of each continent. They include:Export, Industry, Investment and Services. They have been selected because in theory they contribute positively to GDP unlike Import that has negative effect on GDP. in other words, the governments spend on every import to their country which has a negative feedback on GDP.

Although Agriculture has a positive impact on GDP, it will not be considered in this case because Agro is part of a nation's export.

Findings¶

The above graph clear shows that Asia had heavily invested in their industries while maintaing other sectors in good shape compared to the rest of the the world. In addition, the average Asian investment portfolio is equivalent to that of Europe at 25%. According to ADB, Asian Developmental Bank, revealed in one of their publications that the single most important factor that explains East Asias development success was its fast structural transformation toward industrialization, manufacturing in particular.

It is best at this point to narrown down the study down to the countries contributing maximally to the Asian GDP. Let's find out who they are and what they do best.

Outcome of the Guess¶

In contrast to the previous hypothesis that most industrialized countries are also the top leaders in GDP, It turned out that just two contries namely China and Saudi Arabia were on the two top lists throughout the period. Regarding the top industrialized Asian countries, a sudy by NS Energy showed that Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,Saudi Arabia, Iraq were among the top 10 oil producing countries in 2019 which buttress the fact that Asian industrial sector could have been on receiving economic boost supplied by oil producing nations as oppossed to others leading by GDP

Conclusions¶

Broadly speaking, in all the counteries there have been an increase in economic activities leading to econmic growth over the years. However, the growth varied from one continent to the other. It's also found that economic concentartion of individual countries have an overall impact on their continent.

Limitations¶

  • The variables in consideration namely Exports, Industry,Investment, and Indusrty were expressed as mere percentage of their GDP and not the actual figures which makes it difficult to pin point by how much the continents/countries varied from one sector to the others because there are other metrics invloved in GDP calculation.

  • If the actual fiures were used, incorperating population into the dataset would have revealed a lot more variations in all the continents.
